he changing circumstances of the political, economic, ecclesiastical, artistic, and social history of that continent, it is important to understand epidemic disease and society's response to it.To date, the largest portion of scholarship about plague has focused on its political, economic, demographic, and medical aspects. This interdisciplinary volume offers greater coverage of the religious and the psychological dimensions of plague and of European society's response to it through many centuries and over a wide geographical terrain, including Byzantium. This research draws extensively upon a wealth of primary sources, both printed and painted, and includes ample bibliographical reference to the most important secondary sources, providing much new insight into how generations of Europeans responded to this dread disease.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aPietyxHistory. 0aPlaguexReligious aspectsxHistory. 0aPlaguezEuropexHistoryy16th century. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 16th Century.2bisacsh1 aBarker, Sheila, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerger, Pamela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEamon, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGertsman, Elina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHipp, Elisabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaldellis, Anthony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMormando, Franco, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMormando, Franco, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRittgers, Ronald K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWorcester, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/r